# Technical Overview: VR, AR, and Space Technology

---

## What is VR?
In recent times, we use various technologies to consume media, watch movies or just doomscroll. Basically, we just spend a lot of time on our screens. **Virtual Reality or VR** is a type of technology that uses a headset with a similar built-in screen to display a virtual environment for interactive experiences and exploration of digital tech. It is a stimulated experience which gives the user an immersive feel of reality. It enables us to visualise and understand complex concepts by producing realistic images or recreating various sounds and sensations. This is possible due to the equipment, which includes gyroscopes for motion tracking, HD screen for images, processors and other components. This stimulation is strongly oriented to the real world. The software includes computer graphics, audios and other sensory inputs. There is quite a lot of development going on in this field. We have come a long way, from experiencing VR through YouTube videos to using Generative AI algorithms to build realistic simulations.

---

## What is the difference b/w AR and VR?
Firstly, **AR or Augmented Reality** is a similar type of tech as VR that makes us have an immersive experience. But instead of transporting you to the virtual world, it takes digital images and layers them on the real world.

* Virtual reality aims to create a virtual experience with headsets and tracking to place the user in a different world. Augmented reality focuses on augmenting the physical world with digital artifacts, images, videos, or experiences overlayed with computer-generated imagery (CGI) and 3D models. 
* AR uses a camera to allow you to interact with the physical world via a digital overlay. VR immerses you fully into a digital world via a headset, sound, and haptic feedback.
* AR changes the way interaction between humans and machines occurs by bypassing the need for physical controls in the future through the use of virtual control panels. Whereas, in VR, users must control the visuals with hardware itself yet, it creates a sensory experience by stimulating and tricking the sensory organs into interacting with the virtual world as they would the physical world.  

